04817nam a22007215i 9781400825912DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092004nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008259127 a10.1515/97814008259122doi  a(DE-B1597)446285  a(OCoLC)979576699  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPA4247b.L37 2004 7aPER0110202bisacsh04a882.011 aLape, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReproducing Athens :bMenander's Comedy, Democratic Culture, and the Hellenistic City /cSusan Lape.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2009] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- t1. Narratives of Resistance and Romance -- t2. Reproducing Democracy in Oligarchic and Autocratic Athens -- t3. Making Citizens in Comedy and Court -- t4. The Ethics of Democracy in Menander’s Dyskolos -- t5. The Politics of Sexuality in Drama and Democratic Athens -- t6. The Mercenary Romance -- t7. Trials of Masculinity in Democratic Discourse and Menander’s Sikyōnioi -- t8. Conclusion: Inevitable Reproduction? -- tBibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReproducing Athens examines the role of romantic comedy, particularly the plays of Menander, in defending democratic culture and transnational polis culture against various threats during the initial and most fraught period of the Hellenistic Era. Menander's romantic comedies--which focus on ordinary citizens who marry for love--are most often thought of as entertainments devoid of political content. Against the view, Susan Lape argues that Menander's comedies are explicitly political. His nationalistic comedies regularly conclude by performing the laws of democratic citizen marriage, thereby promising the generation of new citizens. His transnational comedies, on the other hand, defend polis life against the impinging Hellenistic kingdoms, either by transforming their representatives into proper citizen-husbands or by rendering them ridiculous, romantic losers who pose no real threat to citizen or city. In elaborating the political work of romantic comedy, this book also demonstrates the importance of gender, kinship, and sexuality to the making of democratic civic ideology. Paradoxically, by championing democratic culture against various Hellenistic outsiders, comedy often resists the internal status and gender boundaries on which democratic culture was based. Comedy's ability to reproduce democratic culture in scandalous fashion exposes the logic of civic inclusion produced by the contradictions in Athens's desperately politicized gender system. Combining careful textual analysis with an understanding of the context in which Menander wrote, Reproducing Athens profoundly changes the way we read his plays and deepens our understanding of Athenian democratic culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aComedy. 0aDemocracy in literature. 0aPolitical plays, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezGreecezAthens. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140082591240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400825912423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400825912.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHAL